Introduction

This analysis takes a look at physicochemical analysis data collected form red wine and white wine samples plus quality ratings assigned to each sample by wine experts. A random forest model is built to predict quality rating from the chemical properties of wine.

Data was obtained from UCI Data Repository and was contributed by Paulo Cortez, University of Minho, Guimaraes, Portugal.

Import Packages

source("C:/_stuff/r.code.snippets/all.imports.R")

Load Data

There are two datasets one each for the red and white variants of the Portuguese Vinho Verde wine. The variables are chemical characterstics of the wines. The response is the Quality rating assigned by wine experts (the median of at least 3 evaluations) expert graded the wine quality. Ratings are 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

wine.r <- read.csv("C:/_data/wine.quality/winequality-red.csv", sep=";")
wine.w <- read.csv("C:/_data/wine.quality/winequality-white.csv", sep=";")

wine.r$quality <- as.factor(wine.r$quality)
wine.w$quality <- as.factor(wine.w$quality)

Pairs Plot with Additional Detail

The bottom left of the matrix contains scatter plots, the upper right of the matrix contains the correlation between the two attributes, and the diagonal contain the variable histogram.

source("C:/_stuff/r.code.snippets/pairs.panels.R")
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
pairs(wine.r,lower.panel=panel.smooth, upper.panel=panel.cor,diag.panel=panel.hist, main="Red Wine Data Correlation Plots")

pairs(wine.w,lower.panel=panel.smooth, upper.panel=panel.cor,diag.panel=panel.hist, main="White Wine Data Correlation Plots")

Variables with strong correlations.

In red wine, * fixed.acidity and density have a 0.668 correlation coefficient; both are commparably correlated to the response, quality * fixed.acidity and citric.acid have a 0.672 correlation coefficient; citric.acid is more strongly correlated to the response, quality. * fixed.acidity and pH have a -0.683 correlation coefficient; fixed.acidity is more strongly correlated to the response, quality. * free.sulfur.dioxide and total sulfur dioxide have a 0.668 correlation coefficient; while total.sulfur.dioxide is more strongly correlated to the response, quality.

In white wine, * density and residual.sugar have a 0.839 correlation coefficient; density is more strongly correlated to the response, quality. * density and alcohol have a -0.780 correlation coefficient; both are almost equally correlated (in opposite directions) to the response, quality. * free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide have a 0.616 correlation coefficient; total.sulfur.dioxide is more strongly correlated to the response, quality.

After removing the correlated variables, prediction performance was not signnificantly improved, and in the case of white wine, was degraded slightly. All predictor variables will be kept.

Although the centered and scale the predictors deliver a slightly better prediction accuracy, the difference is not significant enough to justify the pre-processing of unseen data.

An assessment of prediction performance when predictors were scaled and centered versus not indicated that pre-processing the predictors improved the accuracy of the prediction slightly. The data will be not be centered and scaled and predictors will not be removed.

# create temp data frames for analysis
wine.rs <- wine.r
wine.ws <- wine.w

Separate into training and test data sets

Separated 2/3 of observations into training set, and 1/3 of observations into the test set.

train.ids.rs <- sample(nrow(wine.rs),(nrow(wine.rs)/3)*2)
wine.rs.train <- wine.rs[train.ids.rs,]
wine.rs.test <- wine.rs[-train.ids.rs,]

train.ids.ws <- sample(nrow(wine.ws),(nrow(wine.ws)/3)*2)
wine.ws.train <- wine.ws[train.ids.ws,]
wine.ws.test <- wine.ws[-train.ids.ws,]

Train the Models in Training Set

Build model for red wine quality predictions. Although the document ManualSetting Up, Using, And Understanding Random Forests V4.0 indicates that cross-validation is not needed to get an unbiased estimate of the test set error, it was used as best practice when building models.

Build model to predict red wine quality rating.

set.seed(10)
m.winers.cv <- train(quality~., data=wine.rs.train, method="rf",
                  trControl = trainControl(method = "cv"))
m.winers.cv$finalModel
